# Prerequisite Gate — Stop Before You Help

Before running `npx @pacaf/wizard-ux@latest`, `pac` commands, `dotnet tool install`, or any tool that depends on Node.js/.NET/Python, **verify the user has the prerequisites installed**.

## When to gate
- Fresh repo (no `package.json`, no `src/`, no `power.config.json`)
- User says "set up", "run the wizard", "get me started", "new machine"
- A command in this session failed with `command not found` / `is not recognized` / `npx: command not found` / `pac: command not found`

## The check (one at a time, no `&&`)
```bash
node --version
npm --version
git --version
dotnet --version
pac help
```
Windows: `py -V`. macOS/Linux: `python3 --version`.

## Before declaring missing — probe canonical install path

Many "command not found" reports are PATH problems, not install problems. The classic macOS/zsh case: a `PATH` entry that contains a literal unexpanded `~` (e.g. `~/.dotnet/tools`). zsh and bash do not tilde-expand inside `PATH` — `which pac` fails even though `$HOME/.dotnet/tools/pac` exists and runs.

Before firing the missing-tool stop block, test the canonical install path directly:

| Tool | macOS / Linux | Windows |
|---|---|---|
| `pac` | `$HOME/.dotnet/tools/pac` | `%USERPROFILE%\.dotnet\tools\pac.exe` |
| `dotnet` | `/usr/local/share/dotnet/dotnet` | `%ProgramFiles%\dotnet\dotnet.exe` |
| `node` | `/usr/local/bin/node`, `/opt/homebrew/bin/node` | `%ProgramFiles%\nodejs\node.exe` |
| `git` | `/usr/bin/git`, `/usr/local/bin/git`, `/opt/homebrew/bin/git` | `%ProgramFiles%\Git\cmd\git.exe` |

If the binary runs from the absolute path but `which`/`Get-Command` fails, this is a **broken PATH**, not a **missing tool**. Output the PATH-fix stop block — do not advise reinstalling:

```
🛑 <Tool> installed but not on PATH

<Tool> exists at <canonical path> but the shell cannot find it.
On macOS/Linux this is almost always a PATH entry containing a literal `~`.

  # zsh (macOS default)
  echo 'export PATH="$HOME/.dotnet/tools:$PATH"' >> ~/.zshrc && exec zsh

  # PowerShell (Windows)
  [Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable(
    'Path', "$env:Path;$env:USERPROFILE\.dotnet\tools", 'User')
```

## If a tool is genuinely missing — STOP

Output:
```
🛑 Prerequisite missing — only you can install this

  ❌ <Tool> — <why needed>
       Install: <official link>
       Verify:  <command>

✅ Already installed: <passing tools>

Why I can't do this for you: installer/admin/PATH — close and reopen the
VS Code terminal after install, then say "ready" and I'll re-check.

Full guide: docs/prerequisite-setup.md
```
Then stop. Do not auto-`winget`/`brew`/`choco`/`apt` — those have their own elevation, proxy, and SSL-inspection failure modes you will end up debugging.

## Windows gotchas
- `python3` → Microsoft Store stub. Test with `py -V`.
- VS Code default terminal often `cmd.exe`. Command Palette → **Terminal: Select Default Profile** → **PowerShell**.
- `pac` lives in `%USERPROFILE%\.dotnet\tools` — restart terminal after `dotnet tool install`.
- `npx` exit code 9009 = Node missing or terminal not restarted.
- Corporate SSL inspection → cert errors on `npm`/`dotnet`/`pip`. Diagnose, do not retry.
- OneDrive Files On-Demand → permission errors. Recommend "Always keep on this device" or move repo.

## macOS gotchas
- First `git --version` triggers Xcode CLT GUI installer (user-only).
- Homebrew on Apple Silicon = `/opt/homebrew`; Intel = `/usr/local`. Must `eval "$(/opt/homebrew/bin/brew shellenv)"`.
- **`PATH` entries with literal `~` are silently broken in zsh/bash.** Use `$HOME/.dotnet/tools`, not `~/.dotnet/tools`. The canonical-path probe above catches this.

## Dataverse intent? HARD GATE on the Dataverse-skills plugin
All Dataverse work is delegated to the **[microsoft/Dataverse-skills](https://github.com/microsoft/Dataverse-skills)** plugin — first-class, only-supported, **not optional**. Any Dataverse intent (provision/modify/query tables, columns, relationships, option sets, forms, views; import/seed/export/bulk-edit data; solution lifecycle; org structure) + plugin not installed/verified ⇒ **STOP** before any Dataverse op. Does not fire for pure Code App scaffold, non-Dataverse connectors, or planning 00a–00e before schema.

Detect (read-only): (1) files — `[ -d "$HOME/.copilot/installed-plugins/awesome-copilot/dataverse/skills" ]` (Copilot) / `~/.claude*` cache (Claude); (2) `python3 -c "import pandas, PowerPlatform_Dataverse_Client"`; (3) a `list_tables` MCP call succeeds (tools load only after an editor/CLI **restart**). If missing, STOP; branch install by agent (`packages/scripts/detect-agent.mjs`): Copilot `/plugin install dataverse@awesome-copilot`; Claude `claude plugin install dataverse@claude-plugins-official`; then `pip install PowerPlatform-Dataverse-Client pandas`, restart, say "ready". Don't hand-roll Web API/FetchXML or script the plugin install (interactive).

## If this IS the PACAF monorepo source tree — gate on `pnpm install` + build

The checks above only cover **consumers** running `npx @pacaf/wizard-ux@latest` (published artifact, self-contained). They do **not** cover **contributors** working inside the PACAF source repo who try to run the wizard / scripts / rebrand tool from source. In that case the workspace `node_modules` and built artifacts are missing and the wizard crashes with `Cannot find package 'fastify'` (or similar) which looks like a PACAF bug. It isn't.

Detect the source tree: presence of **all** of `pnpm-workspace.yaml`, `packages/wizard-ux/package.json`, and `packages/agent-instructions/package.json` at the workspace root.

If detected, before suggesting `pnpm --filter ... dev`, `node packages/.../bin/...`, or any local wizard invocation:

```bash
[ -d node_modules ] && [ -d packages/wizard-ux/node_modules ] && echo "✅ installed" || echo "❌ run: pnpm install"
[ -d packages/wizard-ux/dist ] && echo "✅ built" || echo "❌ run: pnpm --filter @pacaf/wizard-ux build"
```

If either fails, stop and tell the user:

```
🛑 Monorepo source tree — workspace not ready

Run:
  pnpm install
  pnpm --filter @pacaf/wizard-ux build

End users do NOT need this — `npx @pacaf/wizard-ux@latest` is self-contained.
```

Does **not** apply to downstream Code App repos (no `pnpm-workspace.yaml`, no `packages/wizard-ux/`).

Full details: `.github/instructions/00-prereq-gate.instructions.md`
